ance who came over with the Norman conquest.","Irish: Anglicized (part translated) form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gríobhtha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Gríobhtha</i>’, a personal name from <i>gríobh</i> ‘gryphon’."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffing","meanings":["Variant of   Griffin  ."]},{"name":"Griffee","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gríobhtha</b> (see   Griffin  )."]},{"name":"Griffy","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gríobhtha</b> (see   Griffin  )."]},{"name":"Griffey","meanings":["Irish (Clare): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Gríobhtha</b> (see   Griffin  )."]},{"name":"Griffen","meanings":["Irish (Cork): variant of   Griffin  ."]}]},{"name":"Harold","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>here</i> ‘army’ + <i>weald</i> ‘ruler’. In pre-Conquest England, this was reinforced by the related Old Norse name <i>Haraldr</i>, introduced by Scandinavian settlers. The name was not at all popular in England after the Conquest, probably because of its association with the unfortunate  King Harold , killed at the Battle of Hastings in  1066 . It was used in some parts of Nottinghamshire in the 16th and 17th centuries, and revived more generally, along with a number of other Old English names, in the 19th century, when it suddenly became extremely popular."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Harold William Griffin was born in 1420, in Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England as the son of Nicholas Griffin. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in 1500, in Longnor, Shropshire, England, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1420–1500":"1420–1500","1446–1490":"1446–1490","1400–1482":"1400–1482","1446":"1446","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","6 May 1482":"6. mai 1482","1420":"1420","1482":"1482","1490":"1490","Northampton, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England","Longnor, Shropshire, England":"Longnor, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"1420–1500":"1420–1500","1446–1490":"1446–1490","1400–1482":"1400–1482","1446":"1446","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","6 May 1482":"6. toukokuuta 1482","1420":"1420","1482":"1482","1490":"1490","Northampton, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England","Longnor, Shropshire, England":"Longnor, Shropshire, England"},"fr":{"1420–1500":"1420–1500","1446–1490":"1446–1490","1400–1482":"1400–1482","1446":"1446","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","6 May 1482"